<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
Female: A medium size ground nesting bee with brownish hair and yellowish scopae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F6661796" captionText="Figure 4. Andrena lagopus (Latreille, 1809) (Kehlen, specimen MNHNL 100056; BOLD identifier MNHNL 162 - 21, one middle leg was used for DNA extraction). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Wing, showing submarginal cells; d. Propodeum; e. Abdomen, showing band and punctures in the tergites. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501350" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">4</figureCitation>
a and b). This species is characterised by having only 2 submarginal cells, despite being an 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Andrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F6661796" captionText="Figure 4. Andrena lagopus (Latreille, 1809) (Kehlen, specimen MNHNL 100056; BOLD identifier MNHNL 162 - 21, one middle leg was used for DNA extraction). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Wing, showing submarginal cells; d. Propodeum; e. Abdomen, showing band and punctures in the tergites. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501350" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">4</figureCitation>
c). The middle part of the propodeum is coarsely wrinkled, clearly defined against the sides (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F6661796" captionText="Figure 4. Andrena lagopus (Latreille, 1809) (Kehlen, specimen MNHNL 100056; BOLD identifier MNHNL 162 - 21, one middle leg was used for DNA extraction). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Wing, showing submarginal cells; d. Propodeum; e. Abdomen, showing band and punctures in the tergites. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501350" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">4</figureCitation>
d). The abdomen presents scarce, interrupted hair bands and densely punctured tergites, with very narrow spaces amongst the punctures on the surface of tergite 2 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F6661796" captionText="Figure 4. Andrena lagopus (Latreille, 1809) (Kehlen, specimen MNHNL 100056; BOLD identifier MNHNL 162 - 21, one middle leg was used for DNA extraction). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Wing, showing submarginal cells; d. Propodeum; e. Abdomen, showing band and punctures in the tergites. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501350" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">4</figureCitation>
e).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Specimen from pilot study (MNHNL100056; BOLD identifier MNHNL162-21): Adult female. Body length of 9.23 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="molecular identification">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Molecular identification</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
The taxonomic annotation is supported by DNA barcoding data. The best percentages of sequence identity were achieved with two specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Latreille" baseAuthorityYear="1809" class="Insecta" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena lagopus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagopus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Andrena lagopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from France (100% each, BOLD identifiers FBHAP970-09 and POLLE2072-19), collected in Alsace and Indre et Loire.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
A univoltine species, that specialises on crucifers (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Brassicaceae</taxonomicName>
) for pollen collection (
<bibRefCitation author="Amiet, F." journalOrPublisher="CSCF &amp; SEG, Neuchatel" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6662312" refString="Amiet, F., Herrmann, M., Mueller, A., Neumeyer, R., 2010. Apidae 6. Fauna Helvetica 26: Andrena, Melitturga, Panurginus, Panurgus. CSCF &amp; SEG, Neuchatel" title="Apidae 6. Fauna Helvetica 26: Andrena, Melitturga, Panurginus, Panurgus" year="2010">Amiet et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Its flight season spans from early April until mid-June in Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="Amiet, F." journalOrPublisher="CSCF &amp; SEG, Neuchatel" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6662312" refString="Amiet, F., Herrmann, M., Mueller, A., Neumeyer, R., 2010. Apidae 6. Fauna Helvetica 26: Andrena, Melitturga, Panurginus, Panurgus. CSCF &amp; SEG, Neuchatel" title="Apidae 6. Fauna Helvetica 26: Andrena, Melitturga, Panurginus, Panurgus" year="2010">Amiet et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="conservation">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Conservation</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Latreille" baseAuthorityYear="1809" class="Insecta" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena lagopus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagopus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Andrena lagopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is regionally classified as &quot;Least Concern (LC)&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Nieto, A." journalOrPublisher="Luxembourg: Publications Office of the European Union" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643307" refString="Nieto, A., Roberts, S. P.M., Kemp, J., Rasmont, P., Kuhlmann, M., Garcia Criado, M., Biesmeijer, J. C., Bogusch, P., Dathe, H. H., De la Rua, P., De Meulemeester, T., Dehon, M., Dewulf, A., Ortiz-Sanchez, F. J., Lhomme, P., Pauly, A., Potts, S. G., Praz, C., Quaranta, M., Radchenko, V. G., Scheuchl, E., Smit, J., Straka, J., Terzo, M., Tomozii, B., Window, J., Michez, D., 2014. European Red List of bees. Luxembourg: Publications Office of the European Union" title="European Red List of bees" year="2014">Nieto et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) as it is widespread across much of western and central Europe, being recorded in nearby countries, such as France, Germany and Switzerland (
<bibRefCitation author="Ratnasingham, SUJEEVAN" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology Notes" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643403" refString="Roberts S. Meulemeester T. Andrena lagopus. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2015 https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/19199520/43510181 2020-12-18T00:00:00+02:00" year="2007">Roberts and Meulemeester 2015</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rasmont, P." journalOrPublisher="Universite de Mons, Mons" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643373" refString="Rasmont, P., Genoud, D., Gadoum, S., Aubert, M., Dufrene, E., Le Goff, G., Mahe, G., Michez, D., Pauly, A., 2017. Hymenoptera Apoidea Gallica: liste des abeilles sauvages de Belgique, France, Luxembourg et Suisse. Universite de Mons, Mons" title="Hymenoptera Apoidea Gallica: liste des abeilles sauvages de Belgique, France, Luxembourg et Suisse." year="2017">Rasmont et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
